such submissions:</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\">Explain to students and researchers outside of the osteopathic profession how their research may build on the evidence base of the osteopathic tenets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\">Encourage these investigators to submit their basic science research articles to the <em>JAOA</em>. Researchers who prefer to publish their studies in basic science journals should be encouraged to submit derivative articles, in which they explain how their original work connects to and supports the tenets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\">Send the <a href=\"http://www.jaoa.org/site/misc/ifora.xhtml\"><em>JAOA</em>\'s Information for Authors</a> to those interested in submitting basic science research or derivative articles with appropriate clinical applications. Also consider sharing the <a href=\"http://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/about/leadership/Pages/tenets-of-osteopathic-medicine.aspx\">AOA\'s Tenets of Osteopathic Medicine</a> page.</p> \r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\">Share the <em>JAOA</em>\'s most recently published basic science research article from the November 2013 issue. Paul R. Standley, PhD, and his colleagues\' <a href=\"http://www.jaoa.org/content/113/11/806.abstract\">article</a>, \"In Vitro Biomechanical Strain Regulation of Fibroblast Wound Healing,\" is an excellent example of how basic science research can serve as an evidence base for the osteopathic tenets.</p>','<p>We\'re on Twitter! Follow The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association (JAOA) on Twitter at <a href=\'https://twitter.com/TheJAOA\'>@TheJAOA</a> for updates, highlights, and conversations about the JAOA and osteopathic medical research.</p>','<p>SCOPUS <a href=\"http://www.scimagojr.com/compare.php?j1=Journal+of+the+American+Osteopathic+Association%2C+The&amp;j2=American+Family+Physician&amp;j3=Physical+Medicine+and+Rehabilitation+Clinics+of+North+America&amp;j4=International+Journal+of+Osteopathic+Medicine&amp;un=journals&amp;inj=0\" style=\"color: rgb(17, 31, 67);\">has released</a> its SCImage journal rankings for 2012. JAOA rankings have gone up for the second year in a row. Check out the JAOA\'s SCImago Journal &amp; Country ranking.<p>','<p>\"I would like more information and guidance about how to promote the JAOA to my colleagues and institution.\"</p>','http://www.do-online.org/JAOA/connections/poll/vote-form.php?poll=11','<h2 style=\"margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 17px; color: rgb(17, 31, 67); margin-top: 3px;\">Michael A. Seffinger, DO</h2>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">Professor and chair of the Department of NMM/OMM at the Western University of Health Sciences College of Osteopathic Medicine in the Pacific and the Pacific Northwest, and <em>JAOA</em> associate editor</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">Michigan State University College of Osteopathic Medicine, Class of 1988</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">I want to contribute to this vital communication link that keeps the osteopathic profession alive and viable. I want to facilitate open and productive scientific, peer-reviewed discourse among osteopathic physicians and our students in particular, as well as anyone else interested in osteopathic medicine. I want to promote the JAOA as a professional scientific journal that is interactive, evidence based, and up to date with state-of-the-art concepts about health and disease from an osteopathic perspective.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">Whether it is meaningful to our profession, makes a significant contribution to the scientific literature, describes valid and appropriate methodology, reviews pertinent literature, clearly and accurately reports and interprets the data, and states the conclusions based only on the data obtained.&nbsp;The manuscript should make sense, state its limitations and strengths, and make recommendations for further study.</p>','allen.jpg',NULL),(80,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1 style=\"color: rgb(17, 31, 76); font-size: 15px; margin: 10px 20px 0px;\">Memorable Research</h1>','<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\">Which <em>JAOA</em> articles have had the greatest effect on patient care and/or research? What made these articles more impactful than other articles on a similar topic? <em>JAOA</em> Associate Editor Michael A. Seffinger, DO, is asking for your help in compiling a comprehensive timeline of the <em>JAOA</em>’s most impactful articles published from January 2000 through December 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n  <li><strong>Consider your learning style.</strong> Do you comprehend data better when it is presented in the text as opposed to a table?</li> \r\n\r\n  <li><strong>Remain objective.</strong> Research articles you or your closest colleagues have personally worked on may be the most impactful in your memory—dig deeper.</li>\r\n\r\n  <li><strong>Look for historical significance.</strong> Has a recent historical or societal event helped influence a significant contribution to osteopathic research? History does repeat itself after all…</li>\r\n\r\n  <li><strong>Consider the source.</strong> The osteopathic profession has a strong traditional background. Ponder the author’s supporting evidence.</li>\r\n</ul>','<p>Thank you for your participation in the Doodle Survey. Spring has just barely sprung, but OMED 2013 will be here before you know it. Stay tuned for more information regarding the JAOA Editorial Advisory Board meeting.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 14px; color: rgb(17, 31, 67); line-height: 18px; font-weight: bold; margin: 3px 20px 6px; text-align: left;\">View JAOA Peer Reviewers’ poll results regarding author confidentiality under “My Committees” on <a href=\"http://www.osteopathic.org\">Osteopathic.org</a>.</p>','<p>“Would JAOA readership benefit from publishing various theme issues in the future”</p>','http://','<h2>Dennis J. Dowling, DO</h2>','<p>Director of Osteopathic Manipulative Medicine, Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation Department, Nassau University Medical Center</p>','<p>New York College of Osteopathic Medicine, Class of 1989</p>','<p>The JAOA represents the opportunity to present uniquely osteopathic medicine research in an evidence-based approach that supports osteopathic principles, philosophy, and practice.</p>','<p>the contributor(s) who has the best interest of the profession in mind when submitting their articles. I try to assist by clarifying the aspects that are unclear, exposing inconsistencies that can be addressed, suggesting expansions where the information is sparse, and summarizing when the sections are overlong. An article should present either novel research that elucidates osteopathic concerns, research that supports osteopathic concepts in a novel manner, or articles that can assist those within and outside the profession to better understand and utilize osteopathic medicine.</p>','allen.jpg',NULL),(81,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1>***HEADLINE***</h1>','<p>***MAIN*BODY*TEXT***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN*KICKER***</p>','<p>***ONLINE*POLL*QUESTION***</p>','http://','<h2>***PEER*NAME***</h2>','<p>***PEER*OCCUPATION***</p>','<p>***PEER*SCHOOL***</p>','<p>***PEER*INVOLVED*BECAUSE***</p>','<p>***PEER*WHEN*REVIEWING***</p>','hensel.jpg',NULL),(82,'Peer Reviewers','Winter',2014,'<h1 style=\"color: rgb(17, 31, 76); font-size: 15px; line-height: 20px; margin: 10px 20px 0px;\">Peer Reviewer’s Potential: An Original Contribution Abstract</h1>','<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Context:</strong> Quality peer reviews evaluate the originality, scientific impact, quality, and appropriateness of manuscripts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Objective:</strong> To advance the osteopathic medical profession through critical review of research submitted to the <em>JAOA</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Methods:</strong> Up to 4 peer reviewers per manuscript were tasked with providing feedback. Because peer reviewers are experts in their fields, manuscripts were expected to undergo careful and objective consideration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Results:</strong> Peer reviewers were inclusive in their responses to authors, encouraging more structurally efficient and innovative research to be published in the <em>JAOA</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"main_body_text_to_edit\" style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Conclusion:</strong> The quality of research published in the <em>JAOA</em> was at an all-time high, thus advancing the osteopathic medical profession.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 14px; color: rgb(253, 197, 120); line-height: 22px; margin: 10px 20px; text-align: left;\">The American Osteopathic Association (AOA) is pleased to announce its 14th editor in chief, Robert Orenstein, DO. Currently an associate professor of medicine at the Mayo Clinic College of Medicine in Rochester, Minnesota, and the chair of the Division of Infectious Diseases at the Mayo Clinic in Phoenix, Arizona, Dr Orenstein began contributing to <em>The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association</em> (<em>JAOA</em>) in 2010 as a section editor of “Evidence-Based Clinical Reviews.”</p>','<p>Check out the <a href=\"http://www.jaoa.org/content/current\" title=\"Table of Contents — January 2014, 114 (1) \">2013 SOMA &amp; BIOM Abstracts and Poster Competition</a> results available online now in the January 2014 issue.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px 20px 10px 15px; text-align: left;\">\"Which of the following is not acceptable practice for peer reviewers when reviewing original contributions?\"</p>','http://www.do-online.org/JAOA/connections/poll/vote-form.php?poll=21','<h2 style=\"margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 17px; color: rgb(17, 31, 67); margin-top: 3px;\">Kendi L. Hensel, DO, PhD</h2>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">Associate professor in the Department of Osteopathic Manipulative Medicine at the University of North Texas Health Science Center Texas College of Osteopathic Medicine.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">Oklahoma State University College of Osteopathic Medicine, Class of 1998</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">I enjoy research, and I believe strongly that our profession must become more research literate. We must all know how to read research and draw our own conclusions so that we can make appropriate decisions about the clinical relevance of the research.</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 13px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 17px; margin: 0px; text-align: left;\">I look for clarity of writing, completeness of description, and accuracy of the conclusions. I also look for any overstatement of results, as well as conclusions that are being drawn on unsupported statements.</p>','hensel.jpg',NULL),(83,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1>***HEADLINE***</h1>','<p>***MAIN*BODY*TEXT***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN*KICKER***</p>','<p>***ONLINE*POLL*QUESTION***</p>','http://','<h2>***PEER*NAME***</h2>','<p>***PEER*OCCUPATION***</p>','<p>***PEER*SCHOOL***</p>','<p>***PEER*INVOLVED*BECAUSE***</p>','<p>***PEER*WHEN*REVIEWING***</p>','hensel.jpg',NULL),(84,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1>***HEADLINE***</h1>','<p>***MAIN*BODY*TEXT***</p>','<p style=\"font-size: 14px; color: rgb(253, 197, 120); line-height: 22px; margin: 10px 20px; text-align: left;\">***LEAD*IN***hiya</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN*KICKER***</p>','<p>***ONLINE*POLL*QUESTION***</p>','http://','<h2>***PEER*NAME***</h2>','<p>***PEER*OCCUPATION***</p>','<p>***PEER*SCHOOL***</p>','<p>***PEER*INVOLVED*BECAUSE***</p>','<p>***PEER*WHEN*REVIEWING***</p>','hensel.jpg',NULL),(85,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1>***HEADLINE***</h1>','<p>***MAIN*BODY*TEXT***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN*KICKER***</p>','<p>***ONLINE*POLL*QUESTION***</p>','http://','<h2>***PEER*NAME***</h2>','<p>***PEER*OCCUPATION***</p>','<p>***PEER*SCHOOL***</p>','<p>***PEER*INVOLVED*BECAUSE***</p>','<p>***PEER*WHEN*REVIEWING***</p>','allen.jpg',NULL),(86,'Peer Reviewers','Summer',2014,'<h1>***HEADLINE***</h1>','<p>***MAIN*BODY*TEXT***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN***</p>','<p>***LEAD*IN*KICKER***</p>','<p>***ONLINE*POLL*QUESTION***</p>','http://','<h2>***PEER*NAME***</h2>','<p>***PEER*OCCUPATION***</p>','<p>***PEER*SCHOOL***</p>','<p>***PEER*INVOLVED*BECAUS